00:32:42.330 --> 00:32:45.510
How to keep it away from the
smaller guys, or the guys

00:32:45.510 --> 00:32:46.680
coming after me.

00:32:46.680 --> 00:32:50.440
And so we built a wall of IP,
those 13 patents, of all the

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:52.490
different ways of
protecting it--

00:32:52.490 --> 00:32:55.790
from trademarks, to copyrights,
to patents.

00:32:55.790 --> 00:32:58.470
Now, what's great about that,
I was in federal court

00:32:58.470 --> 00:32:59.640
defending my patents.

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:02.820
A lot of people never get
that great opportunity.

00:33:02.820 --> 00:33:07.290
But a small little toy company,
I showed them my

00:33:07.290 --> 00:33:09.560
idea, they signed NDAs.

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:13.130
And next thing you know, it was
on a number one hit toy.

00:33:13.130 --> 00:33:16.470
And I took that toy company
to court in

00:33:16.470 --> 00:33:17.130
federal courts, San Francisco.

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:19.270
And that toy company was LEGO.

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:24.170
And I remember seeing my name
when I went to the court.

00:33:24.170 --> 00:33:26.650
It was Stephen Key Design
versus LEGO.

00:33:26.650 --> 00:33:31.600
And I realized right then and
there, how do you fight LEGO

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:33.820
when I'm one guy?

00:33:33.820 --> 00:33:38.140
But I realized because of
patents, you can play the

00:33:38.140 --> 00:33:39.710
biggest game in the world.

00:33:39.710 --> 00:33:43.520
And sure enough, three years
before it went to trial.

00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:47.590
Or three years after talking
for three years, two weeks

00:33:47.590 --> 00:33:49.490
before it went to trial
we settled.

00:33:49.490 --> 00:33:51.040
So patents are important.

00:33:51.040 --> 00:33:53.450
But getting back, why do
you use attorneys?

00:33:53.450 --> 00:33:55.390
When you have big ideas,
you need to talk

00:33:55.390 --> 00:33:57.280
about long-term strategy.

00:33:57.280 --> 00:34:00.190
Simple ideas, maybe
yes, maybe no.

00:34:00.190 --> 00:34:03.150
A lot of companies don't care
about patents with simple

00:34:03.150 --> 00:34:06.150
ideas because they come
and go so quick.

00:34:06.150 --> 00:34:08.500
If you waited for a patent
to issue, you might

00:34:08.500 --> 00:34:10.870
be waiting too long.

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:14.980
So for simple ideas, PPA is
a very powerful tool.

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:18.150
But if you've got a big
strategy, talk to someone that

00:34:18.150 --> 00:34:21.130
understands IP and how to build
your wall going forward

00:34:21.130 --> 00:34:22.010
to keep everybody out.

00:34:22.010 --> 00:34:23.994
Because when you have
a wall, you know

00:34:23.994 --> 00:34:25.679
what it says to everybody?

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:27.650
This guy is serious.

00:34:27.650 --> 00:34:30.249
And it sends that message.

00:34:30.249 --> 00:34:32.100
So that's when I use
my attorneys.

00:34:32.100 --> 00:34:34.969
And also, every licensing
agreement that I ever sign, I

00:34:34.969 --> 00:34:37.080
always have a licensing attorney
look it over to make

00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:40.070
sure I haven't missed something
along the way.

00:34:40.070 --> 00:34:42.505
Because they get very technical
at some point.

00:34:42.505 --> 00:34:43.850
AUDIENCE: Thank you, Stephen.

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:44.480
Quick question.

00:34:44.480 --> 00:34:47.679
It looks like you've been
successful both routes, with

00:34:47.679 --> 00:34:50.370
licensing and then building
companies, and

00:34:50.370 --> 00:34:52.489
running those companies.

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:56.239
What would you say is kind of
your litmus test or your

00:34:56.239 --> 00:35:00.270
thought process for knowing when
to license versus when to

00:35:00.270 --> 00:35:02.920
create, build, and
run a company?

00:35:02.920 --> 00:35:04.050
STEPHEN KEY: Great,
great question.

00:35:04.050 --> 00:35:06.160
How do you know what path
you want to take?

00:35:06.160 --> 00:35:09.470
It's the same path at
the very beginning.

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:11.430
You want to, first of all,
do your homework.

00:35:11.430 --> 00:35:13.070
Test the marketplace.

00:35:13.070 --> 00:35:14.080
Study the marketplace.

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:15.530
That means go down to
the store, see if

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:16.860
your product's there.

00:35:16.860 --> 00:35:18.620
Do a prior art search.

00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:23.230
Look at the whole environment
to see.

00:35:23.230 --> 00:35:24.860
And then ask yourself
a couple questions.

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:28.120
Number one, can my
product be made?

00:35:28.120 --> 00:35:30.430
And a lot of inventors don't
ask that, or entrepreneurs.

00:35:30.430 --> 00:35:33.580
Can it be made at a price where
everybody makes money?

00:35:33.580 --> 00:35:35.660
Number two, does it
have a wow factor?

00:35:35.660 --> 00:35:37.990
Can I describe it in one
sentence that people go, hey,

00:35:37.990 --> 00:35:40.540
I want more?

00:35:40.540 --> 00:35:45.760
And also, I like to look at
it, how big is the market?

00:35:45.760 --> 00:35:47.760
So I use those things
to kind of test it.

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:50.060
But at the end of the day,
even if I wanted to

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:54.490
manufacture an idea, I might
try to license it first

00:35:54.490 --> 00:35:56.130
because I want to hear what
other people say.

00:35:56.130 --> 00:35:58.230
Even if it's negative, I want
to hear why they're

00:35:58.230 --> 00:35:59.900
saying no, no, no.

00:35:59.900 --> 00:36:01.840
I want to hear it because I can
adjust it, I can turn it,

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:03.420
I can change it.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:06.620
So for me, I just look
at it that way.

00:36:06.620 --> 00:36:09.340
Some ideas cannot be licensed.

00:36:09.340 --> 00:36:11.675
And what I liked about the
guitar pick, it was so simple

00:36:11.675 --> 00:36:14.110
it was like, well, I can put
a million guitar picks

00:36:14.110 --> 00:36:14.910
underneath the table.

00:36:14.910 --> 00:36:17.490
Why don't we do that?

00:36:17.490 --> 00:36:20.040
And what was really fun about
it, it was easy to do and it

00:36:20.040 --> 00:36:20.940
was a blast.

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:24.000
It was probably the funnest
thing I've ever done.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.670
And it was just with a
simple guitar pick.

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:28.935
So that's how I do it.

00:36:28.935 --> 00:36:30.440
You keep on learning
along the way.

00:36:30.440 --> 00:36:34.424
And soon enough, you'll see
where you want to take it.

00:36:34.424 --> 00:36:36.030
AUDIENCE: So I have a little
more skepticism.

00:36:36.030 --> 00:36:39.080
My dad did this for a few
decades and he sold games and

00:36:39.080 --> 00:36:40.780
toys to Mattel and various
other companies--

00:36:40.780 --> 00:36:41.930
reasonable at it.

00:36:41.930 --> 00:36:44.140
But most people don't do
very well at this.

00:36:44.140 --> 00:36:46.190
There's a lot of
people who try.

00:36:46.190 --> 00:36:50.070
There are a lot of studies
showing that more--

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:52.070
other than in the pharmaceutical
industry,

00:36:52.070 --> 00:36:54.300
patents cost more to the patent
holders than they

00:36:54.300 --> 00:36:55.470
receive from the patent.

00:36:55.470 --> 00:36:59.020
That it's definitely an atypical
story that you have.

00:36:59.020 --> 00:37:00.380
So--

00:37:00.380 --> 00:37:01.140
STEPHEN KEY: What's
the reality?

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:02.370
AUDIENCE: Yeah, what's
the reality?

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:04.310
I mean, you take a look at
a company like Google.

00:37:04.310 --> 00:37:06.010
You want to come talk to us.

00:37:06.010 --> 00:37:08.450
We're going to make you sign a
contract saying that anything

00:37:08.450 --> 00:37:10.770
you say to us is fine,
we can use that.

00:37:10.770 --> 00:37:12.300
A lot of companies do that.

00:37:12.300 --> 00:37:13.760
That's why you're scared of
the legal department.

00:37:13.760 --> 00:37:15.990
If the legal department gets
involved, almost all big

00:37:15.990 --> 00:37:18.820
companies will throw one of
those contracts at you and not

00:37:18.820 --> 00:37:22.280
want to do this.

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:23.626
I think it's great that you've
done what you've done, but I

00:37:23.626 --> 00:37:25.420
think the reality is it's
not nearly as rosy.

00:37:25.420 --> 00:37:27.110
STEPHEN KEY: Well, let's
talk about reality.

00:37:27.110 --> 00:37:29.020
And I think that's
a great question.

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:31.850
97% of all patents never
make the money it

00:37:31.850 --> 00:37:33.730
costs to file them.

00:37:33.730 --> 00:37:34.950
97%.

00:37:34.950 --> 00:37:36.530
That's huge.

00:37:36.530 --> 00:37:38.440
That's like, who's
making the money?

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:40.214
The attorneys are making
the money, right?

00:37:40.214 --> 00:37:41.830
AUDIENCE: I own one like
that [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:41.830 --> 00:37:43.420
STEPHEN KEY: I don't like
that number either.

00:37:43.420 --> 00:37:46.310
And I always ask why that is.

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:48.330
And I think it's for
a couple reasons.

00:37:48.330 --> 00:37:51.110
Number one, I think people file
patents that shouldn't be

00:37:51.110 --> 00:37:54.260
filing patents because they
haven't tested the market yet.

00:37:54.260 --> 00:37:55.560
They file patents on ideas.

00:37:55.560 --> 00:37:57.800
They don't know if they
can be manufactured.

00:37:57.800 --> 00:38:00.750
So I think there needs to be a
little bit more education.

00:38:00.750 --> 00:38:04.934
But let's talk about it's
a numbers game.

00:38:04.934 --> 00:38:09.310
It's like anything else in life,
if you're-- anything you

00:38:09.310 --> 00:38:11.990
do, if you do it a few times,
your chances of success are

00:38:11.990 --> 00:38:14.800
never going to be that-- never
going to be great.

00:38:14.800 --> 00:38:17.300
If you look at this and say,
look, I'm a creative person.

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:19.030
I'm going to submit a lot
of ideas to companies.

00:38:19.030 --> 00:38:21.540
Your chances of hitting one
are much, much better.

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:23.800
So let me give you an idea of
how many ideas I submit, so

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:25.550
you really know the nuts
and bolts of it.

00:38:25.550 --> 00:38:27.230
Because that's very fair.

00:38:27.230 --> 00:38:29.680
Ohio Art, when I licensed the
one Michael Jordan to them

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:34.420
sold for 10 years, I probably
submitted 100 to them, too.

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:37.380
And they all said, no on
every one of them.

00:38:37.380 --> 00:38:39.450
Absolutely.

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:41.120
So it is a numbers game.

00:38:41.120 --> 00:38:45.170
But what I like to do is that
instead of paying for patents,

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:50.100
file that provisional patent
application, very inexpensive.

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:52.250
Build a relationship with the
company once you start

00:38:52.250 --> 00:38:53.650
submitting to them.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:56.760
And they'll begin to know that
you're going to come back next

00:38:56.760 --> 00:38:58.460
week with another one.

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:01.420
And they'll begin to talk to
you, what are you looking for?

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:03.970
And that's how you really win.

00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:06.150
To license repeatedly, that's
how you do that.

00:39:06.150 --> 00:39:07.090
But let me get back
to your last

00:39:07.090 --> 00:39:11.020
question, too, about patents.

00:39:11.020 --> 00:39:13.290
Yes, there are a lot
of companies.

00:39:13.290 --> 00:39:17.610
Maybe this one here, I'm
not sure that is--

00:39:17.610 --> 00:39:20.410
you're developing a lot
of ideas everywhere.

00:39:20.410 --> 00:39:22.710
So why would you look at someone
from the outside

00:39:22.710 --> 00:39:23.980
because you don't know
what he's doing,

00:39:23.980 --> 00:39:25.660
he's doing, he's doing.

00:39:25.660 --> 00:39:28.240
And that's very confusing
to big companies.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:30.120
We want to open our doors,
but we've got to

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:31.470
protect our own IP.

00:39:31.470 --> 00:39:33.430
And how do we know if
we haven't invented

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:34.250
it before you do?

00:39:34.250 --> 00:39:36.670
And I think what happens, the
way I handle that, I look for

00:39:36.670 --> 00:39:40.950
companies that do have an open
innovation policy, number one.

00:39:40.950 --> 00:39:45.360
And number two, I file my IP.

00:39:45.360 --> 00:39:48.120
And what I mean by I file mine,
I don't worry about what

00:39:48.120 --> 00:39:50.560
they've done because I've
already done my homework.

00:39:50.560 --> 00:39:52.490
That's how I protect myself.

00:39:52.490 --> 00:39:54.780
And if you want to get into a
really big company, I'll give

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:57.100
you one more tip and I'll
go to somebody else.

00:39:57.100 --> 00:40:00.240
Don't go through
the front door.

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:01.540
There's no way I could
go through the

00:40:01.540 --> 00:40:03.090
front door at Google.

00:40:03.090 --> 00:40:03.990
There is no way.

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:05.530
I couldn't do the front
door at Coke.

00:40:05.530 --> 00:40:06.670
There's no way.

00:40:06.670 --> 00:40:08.760
So how do I get through
the front door?

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:11.980
You go through their
ad agency.

00:40:11.980 --> 00:40:14.710
You go to someone that's bigger,
that's almost required

00:40:14.710 --> 00:40:16.860
to show them innovation.

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:20.110
Ad agencies are almost required
to show their clients

00:40:20.110 --> 00:40:20.730
new innovation.

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:24.110
Because if they didn't and
something happened, it

00:40:24.110 --> 00:40:25.970
wouldn't look so great.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:29.300
So I think you have to look at
the culture of the company.

00:40:29.300 --> 00:40:30.150
Are they looking?

00:40:30.150 --> 00:40:31.870
I think you file your own IP.

00:40:31.870 --> 00:40:34.420
And sometimes go in
a different door.

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:37.850
AUDIENCE: Did you find
differences between companies

00:40:37.850 --> 00:40:40.550
in the US and outside
of the US?

00:40:40.550 --> 00:40:41.280
STEPHEN KEY: Are
they different?

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:43.470
AUDIENCE: On that Interaction,
yeah.

00:40:43.470 --> 00:40:45.970
STEPHEN KEY: I haven't found
there's a very big difference.

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:49.100
I licensed a few of my
technology to a company in

00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:50.900
Japan called [? Celex, ?]

00:40:50.900 --> 00:40:53.710
where they had the rotating
label on NESCAFE Coffee.

00:40:53.710 --> 00:40:57.140
And the conversations were a
little bit different, but it

00:40:57.140 --> 00:40:58.320
was all about innovation.

00:40:58.320 --> 00:40:59.990
It's all about, what
do you have--

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:02.530
show us how to make
more money.

00:41:02.530 --> 00:41:04.030
That's the universal language.

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:05.940
How can we sell more?

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:09.650
And I found it was
fairly easy.

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:11.730
A lot of other countries
want more IP.

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:15.030
But then again, at the end of
the day, you realize that it's

00:41:15.030 --> 00:41:18.470
very expensive to file patents
in other countries as well.

00:41:18.470 --> 00:41:21.320
But that gives you a leg up if
you do have some type of IP

00:41:21.320 --> 00:41:21.780
protection.

00:41:21.780 --> 00:41:25.140
But I think any company, ask
them if they embrace open

00:41:25.140 --> 00:41:26.220
innovation, too.

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:27.410
And just talk it through.

00:41:27.410 --> 00:41:29.500
Hopefully you'll get someone
that can understand what

00:41:29.500 --> 00:41:31.260
you're trying to do.

00:41:31.260 --> 00:41:34.730
It's getting larger and
larger and larger.

00:41:34.730 --> 00:41:38.360
But it's happening here in the
United States in a big way.

00:41:38.360 --> 00:41:40.500
AUDIENCE: So how do you
approach ideas?

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:45.030
Do you think about the idea from
a licensee perspective or

00:41:45.030 --> 00:41:47.870
do you think from the end
user perspective?

00:41:47.870 --> 00:41:51.460
When you think about a problem,
do you start finding

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:54.650
a problem that companies
will have or problems

00:41:54.650 --> 00:41:55.680
that users will have?

00:41:55.680 --> 00:41:57.210
STEPHEN KEY: You do both.

00:41:57.210 --> 00:41:59.850
You can license ideas that if
a company has a problem, you

00:41:59.850 --> 00:42:02.280
got a better solution,
absolutely you can.

00:42:02.280 --> 00:42:05.510
Show them how to save money,
how to be more efficient.

00:42:05.510 --> 00:42:06.390
Yes.

00:42:06.390 --> 00:42:08.960
You can also-- there's a lot of
industries, like the hotel

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:12.300
industry, which is huge that
you license ideas in those

00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:15.220
type of service industries,
hospitality industries.

00:42:15.220 --> 00:42:19.700
But I like to look at my
ideas are not that--

00:42:19.700 --> 00:42:20.860
they're not big ideas.

00:42:20.860 --> 00:42:21.660
They're simple ideas.

00:42:21.660 --> 00:42:23.950
I try to put a smile on
someone's face is

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:25.095
what I try to do.

00:42:25.095 --> 00:42:26.630
Or find something a little
bit different.

00:42:26.630 --> 00:42:27.870
But find a problem.

00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:29.790
Find a pain point.

00:42:29.790 --> 00:42:32.300
I don't care if it's in the
kitchen or with your pet,

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:33.980
those are two industries
that are on fire.

00:42:33.980 --> 00:42:35.780
A kitchen gadget.

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:38.670
People are staying home, so
people are looking for those.

00:42:38.670 --> 00:42:42.450
But find the problem, either for
the customer, identify it.

00:42:42.450 --> 00:42:44.560
Or if it's something that can
help a company be more

00:42:44.560 --> 00:42:46.580
efficient, identify that.

00:42:46.580 --> 00:42:51.230
But really understand who
is it going to help?

00:42:51.230 --> 00:42:55.210
And always gear your sell sheet
to that particular pain.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:56.930
And the other thing I forgot
to mention, you know what's

00:42:56.930 --> 00:42:59.030
better than a sell sheet
I talked about?

00:42:59.030 --> 00:43:00.970
A sell sheet is basically when
you're driving down the

00:43:00.970 --> 00:43:03.130
freeway, you see this
huge sign, and

00:43:03.130 --> 00:43:04.830
you get it that fast.

00:43:04.830 --> 00:43:06.100
That's what a sell sheet does.

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:08.540
But you know what else is
working for everybody?

00:43:08.540 --> 00:43:09.970
Are videos.

00:43:09.970 --> 00:43:11.360
Are little YouTube videos.

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:12.750
Wow.

00:43:12.750 --> 00:43:16.780
Make it one minute, show a
problem, show a solution.

00:43:16.780 --> 00:43:19.926
That is the tool that's been
really knocking it down for

00:43:19.926 --> 00:43:21.460
everybody these days.

