Your provisional patent
application only

00:43:31.610 --> 00:43:33.630
lasts for one year.

00:43:33.630 --> 00:43:36.300
So that seems like a
long time, but it's

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:38.300
really not that long.

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:40.200
And I know a lot of
people run into--

00:43:40.200 --> 00:43:42.955
after that year and I've shown
it to people, I've got to file

00:43:42.955 --> 00:43:44.070
a regular application.

00:43:44.070 --> 00:43:45.670
Or if I come up with some
new embodiments,

00:43:45.670 --> 00:43:46.560
I could file again.

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:48.170
Or I'm going to lose
it, right?

00:43:48.170 --> 00:43:49.200
Do this.

00:43:49.200 --> 00:43:51.980
Before you're ready to file,
do your homework first.

00:43:51.980 --> 00:43:54.190
Get ready to go.

00:43:54.190 --> 00:43:57.240
Do your sell sheet, maybe your
prototype, know the companies

00:43:57.240 --> 00:43:57.860
you're going to call.

00:43:57.860 --> 00:43:58.720
Get your hit list together.

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:01.070
So when you file it, boom.

00:44:01.070 --> 00:44:02.400
You're ready to take action.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:06.150
And realize, when you try to
license an idea, call a lot of

00:44:06.150 --> 00:44:07.880
companies up.

00:44:07.880 --> 00:44:10.510
Spend a week just calling
companies up and send them to

00:44:10.510 --> 00:44:12.280
all of the companies
right there.

00:44:12.280 --> 00:44:14.650
Get all the balls up in the air
all at one time and see

00:44:14.650 --> 00:44:15.800
which ones fall.

00:44:15.800 --> 00:44:19.610
And if more than one calls you
back, congratulations.

00:44:19.610 --> 00:44:22.090
AUDIENCE: So you find a problem,
you have to come up

00:44:22.090 --> 00:44:23.090
with a solution.

00:44:23.090 --> 00:44:26.850
What's your creative
process thinking?

00:44:26.850 --> 00:44:31.870
I'm sure you get stuck
many times as we do.

00:44:31.870 --> 00:44:33.490
And how do you solve that?

00:44:33.490 --> 00:44:34.520
STEPHEN KEY: OK.

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:35.275
That's a great question.

00:44:35.275 --> 00:44:38.990
And I think everybody has
their own set of ways of

00:44:38.990 --> 00:44:40.560
coming up with solutions.

00:44:40.560 --> 00:44:44.700
And I have these games
I play for myself.

00:44:44.700 --> 00:44:47.830
And I think a lot of people
that are in the arts play

00:44:47.830 --> 00:44:48.990
these games all the time.

00:44:48.990 --> 00:44:51.520
So it's really, really
easy for them.

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:53.770
And I think that some of us,
that we don't do this every

00:44:53.770 --> 00:44:54.620
day-- it's a little
bit harder.

00:44:54.620 --> 00:44:57.370
But my wife used to say, Steve,
how can you come up

00:44:57.370 --> 00:44:58.860
with all these ideas?

00:44:58.860 --> 00:45:00.810
I used to tell her it's like
going out in the backyard and

00:45:00.810 --> 00:45:01.870
pulling an apple off the tree.

00:45:01.870 --> 00:45:03.820
They're there every day.

00:45:03.820 --> 00:45:05.460
You need to know how to pluck
them off the tree.

00:45:05.460 --> 00:45:08.150
And this is what I do.

00:45:08.150 --> 00:45:11.870
I always look at changing
materials, the first thing.

00:45:11.870 --> 00:45:14.030
What materials can to change?

00:45:14.030 --> 00:45:16.890
And I always try to get myself
in a frame of mind that there

00:45:16.890 --> 00:45:18.250
are no good answers and bad--

00:45:18.250 --> 00:45:20.295
it's just going through a
creative process of turning

00:45:20.295 --> 00:45:21.740
over all the rocks.

00:45:21.740 --> 00:45:22.210
What's underneath?

00:45:22.210 --> 00:45:22.930
What's underneath?

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:24.920
And then I start looking
at it differently.

00:45:24.920 --> 00:45:26.330
I turn it upside down.

00:45:26.330 --> 00:45:27.580
I look from different views.

00:45:27.580 --> 00:45:28.800
I play games.

00:45:28.800 --> 00:45:31.890
One of the games I play is
called mix and match, where I

00:45:31.890 --> 00:45:33.550
try to look at an idea
and I try to bring

00:45:33.550 --> 00:45:34.880
other things to it.

00:45:34.880 --> 00:45:35.660
And what does it do?

00:45:35.660 --> 00:45:37.860
How to expand upon an idea.

00:45:37.860 --> 00:45:40.460
I might do a thing
called what if.

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:41.280
What if it could do this?

00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:42.800
What if it could do that?

00:45:42.800 --> 00:45:43.740
Or solve it.

00:45:43.740 --> 00:45:46.510
So I play these little
child games that

00:45:46.510 --> 00:45:50.150
allow me to open up.

00:45:50.150 --> 00:45:52.110
And then what I like to
do is I go down to

00:45:52.110 --> 00:45:53.865
wherever I am inspired.

00:45:53.865 --> 00:45:57.530
If it's to the movies or to the
mall, or wherever, where

00:45:57.530 --> 00:45:58.720
you get this--

00:45:58.720 --> 00:46:00.200
there's a point where
your mind kind of

00:46:00.200 --> 00:46:01.370
relaxes a little bit.

00:46:01.370 --> 00:46:03.250
Sometimes it's before
bed or in the shower

00:46:03.250 --> 00:46:05.150
that these ideas pop.

00:46:05.150 --> 00:46:05.910
That's how I do it.

00:46:05.910 --> 00:46:07.970
And I don't overwork
my creativity.

00:46:07.970 --> 00:46:10.780
What I found now today, I don't
come up with a lot of

00:46:10.780 --> 00:46:13.340
ideas, but I'm always solving
problems with manufacturing

00:46:13.340 --> 00:46:15.090
now or marketing other areas.

00:46:15.090 --> 00:46:18.090
So if you learn how to
use these tools,

00:46:18.090 --> 00:46:20.060
I think it's endless.

00:46:20.060 --> 00:46:24.430
But you have to find that
way of playing.

00:46:24.430 --> 00:46:25.940
And it seems like you do a lot
of playing here, which I

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:26.720
really do love.

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:28.840
I mean, it's the right
environment.

00:46:28.840 --> 00:46:29.620
Absolutely.

00:46:29.620 --> 00:46:31.760
That's how I do it, anyway.

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:35.360
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:35.360 --> 00:46:36.610
STEPHEN KEY: Thank
you very much.

